                "dcterms:bibliographicCitation": "Please cite: Elizaveta Suturina, Jon G. C. Kragskow, James W. Whipham and Ernest Borysenko. SimpNMR (Software for Ab Initio-assisted Analysis of pNMR Data) and SimpNMR_DB (Curated Database). Online. 14 April 2026. Available from: https://resources.psdi.ac.uk/resource-theme/bb0f915a-8c4d-4d4c-a4ab-aade7f0ecbf4. [accessed YYYY-MM-DD].",
                "psdiDcatExt:displayPriority": 2.0,
                "dcat:Dataset": {
                    "@id": "psdiDcat:data/37ddb0ce-30ab-4928-a1c2-35f719470137",
                    "dcterms:identifier": "https://resources.psdi.ac.uk/data/37ddb0ce-30ab-4928-a1c2-35f719470137",
                    "@type": "dcat:Dataset",
                    "dcterms:title": "SimpNMR_DB (a Curated Database of SimpNMR Inputs)",
                    "rdfs:label": "SimpNMR_DB",
                    "dcterms:type": {
                        "skos:prefLabel": "Dataset",
                        "@type": "skos:Concept",
                        "@id": "http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Dataset"
                    },
                    "dcterms:description": "SimpNMR_DB is a shared collection for ab initio calculations of hyperfine interactions that are used as inputs for SimpNMR. SimpNMR is an open-source python package for analysing paramagnetic NMR data that links Density Functional Theory (DFT) calculations with NMR spectra and helps to assign the peaks and extract the magnetic susceptibility tensor form paramagnetic shifts. This ab initio data is useful for the community involved in computing magnetic properties of molecules due to the difficulty in accurate prediction. It provides access to computational results that are often time consuming to generate, giving researchers a consistent reference point for comparison, method testing, and reproducibility. As the database grows, it will also support benchmarking studies and the development of machine learning models. Therefore we encourage researchers to share their computational files in SimpNMR_DB to benefit the wider community.\nNote that this repository is currently under rapid and active development.",
                    "dcat:keyword": [
                        "PSDI-funding-call-FC1-2025",
                        "pNMR",
                        "paramanetic NMR",
                        "DFT",
                        "Density Functional Theory",
                        "NMR spectra",
                        "magnetic susceptibility"
